    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Pyrosomes are free-swimming colonial organisms related to ascidians, but in which the individual zooids are arranged into a transparent tubular colony that is closed at the one end and open at the other. The colony thus resembles the finger of a glove. The individuals look much like those of colonial ascidians (sea squirts), except that the inhalant and exhalent openings are now at opposite ends of the body. The individuals all face outwards, so that water is sucked in from outside and pumped into the central chamber and out though the open end of the colony, thus propelling it forwards.</p><p>There is a pair of luminescent organs on either side of the inhalant aperture of each zooid and these contain bioluminescent bacteria that produce a bright light when the colony is disturbed (hence the group name pyro = fire, soma = body).</p><p>Most of the previously recognized species have now been amalgamated under this one name and this is now the only valid species reported from South Africa. &nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_1596",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Colony length 50-500 mm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_1597",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Widespread in tropical and temperate seas globally.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Across whole region.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_1598",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Planktonic and not often seen, but at times can become very common &nbsp;and sometimes washed ashore in large numbers. Well know for their ability to bioluminesce when disturbed.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_1599",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Filter-feeders drawing in water though the inhalant siphon and passing it though a mucous net that lines the pharynx. Capable of extracting minute particulate from the water.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_1600",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Colonies grow by budding off new zooids, so can vary greatly in size and number of component individuals. New colonies are formed by sexual reproduction in which the single egg within each zooid is fertilised internally. This then grows into a zooid that buds off 4 other arranged around it. The original zooid then degenerates, except for its tunic, which is retained to form the basic body of the new colony.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_1601",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Unlikely to be confused with other species, except perhaps comb jellies (ctenophores) some of which have a similar transparent and sausage–shaped body, but are formed of a single individual.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_1602",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fourth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 244). <br><br>Gibbons, MJ (1997). An introduction to the Zooplankton of the Benguela Current Region. NBD Goodwood, Western Cape.",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_1603",
            "longText": null,
